{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652269"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:34:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:34:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18526"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18526"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.05,0.1,0.4,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11255"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79792"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11255"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65100"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1853"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"6361"},{"type":"tags","id":"7615"},{"type":"tags","id":"8114"},{"type":"tags","id":"10695"},{"type":"tags","id":"10726"},{"type":"tags","id":"10746"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"10792"},{"type":"tags","id":"11198"},{"type":"tags","id":"11313"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26099"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79792"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents for genetic counselling. Her brother has Duchenne muscular dystrophy, an X-linked recessive condition. She has mild muscle weakness on examination and an elevated creatine kinase level of 850 U/L (20-200).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains her clinical presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Skewed X chromosome inactivation","Autosomal dominant inheritance pattern","Germline mosaicism","Incomplete penetrance of the mutation","Mitochondrial inheritance"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuchenne muscular dystrophy is an X-linked recessive disorder caused by mutations in the dystrophin gene. Males with the condition typically present in early childhood with progressive muscle weakness, while female carriers are usually asymptomatic. However, some female carriers can display mild symptoms due to X-inactivation patterns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe woman\u0027s presentation is best explained by \u003Cstrong\u003Eskewed X chromosome inactivation\u003C/strong\u003E. During early female development, one X chromosome is randomly inactivated in each cell. Usually this results in roughly 50:50 expression of maternal and paternal X chromosomes. However, sometimes this ratio can be skewed, leading to preferential expression of either the normal or mutant X chromosome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal dominant inheritance pattern \u003C/strong\u003Eor \u003Cstrong\u003Emitochondrial inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - Duchenne muscular dystrophy follows X-linked recessive inheritance\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncomplete penetrance of the mutation\u003C/strong\u003E - The variable expression is due to X inactivation patterns rather than reduced penetrance\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGermline mosaicism\u003C/strong\u003E - This refers to mutations present only in reproductive cells and would not explain the patient\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf a female carrier has skewed X inactivation favouring expression of the X chromosome carrying the dystrophin mutation, she may display symptoms of varying severity. This explains why some female carriers of X-linked conditions can be symptomatic while others are asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["X inactivation patterns explain the mosaic phenotypes seen in female carriers of X-linked conditions.","Skewed X inactivation can lead to variable expression of X-linked disorders in females.","X inactivation testing can help diagnose carrier status for X-linked conditions."],"references":["Viggiano E, Ergoli M, Picillo E, Politano L. Determining the role of skewed X-chromosome inactivation in developing muscle symptoms in carriers of Duchenne muscular dystrophy. Hum Genet. 2016 Jul;135(7):685-98. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27098336/","Emery AEH. The muscular dystrophies. Lancet. 2002;359(9307):687\u201395. doi:10.1016/S0140-6736(02)07815-7"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18526"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65100"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T20:24:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T20:25:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11255"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79792"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeading